items.prompt: Where is a bald eagle safe?
items.response:
By: Laurie L. Dove
A bald eagle is one of the most recognizable birds in North America.
iStock/Getty Images
A bald eagle has a lot going for it. It's majestic, it's the national symbol of the United States and it's protected by the Bald and Golden Eagle Protection Act. Yet, as with any bird, bald eagles are vulnerable to predators, disease and human activity. So where are they safest?
A bald eagle's primary predators are humans and other birds of prey. As a result, it has developed some remarkable adaptations to help it survive. For example, it has extremely sharp vision, which allows it to detect movement from a great distance. It also has a keen sense of smell, which allows it to detect prey from a great distance, too.
Bald eagles are most vulnerable to predators when they're young. They are born in tree cavities, where they can hide from predators. As they mature, they move to the water, where they can blend in with the landscape. In fact, bald eagles can be found throughout North America, from Alaska to Florida. They're even found in the Gulf of Mexico.
Bald eagles are also safe from predators when they're asleep. They're known to nap in the trees during the day and take a rest in the water at night.
You might wonder how bald eagles can be safe when they're asleep. You're probably wondering about this because you're thinking about the fact that bald eagles are so big. They're not. They're actually pretty small for birds of prey, measuring just 31 to 37 inches (79 to 94 centimeters) from beak to tail.
But what about their iconic white head feathers? The white feathers are a natural adaptation that helps bald eagles blend in with the landscape. When they're not in flight, they tend to stand still, which allows them to remain unseen by other birds of prey.
Bald eagles also have a large wingspan, which helps them stay safe from other birds of prey. Bald eagles can have a wingspan of 6 to 8 feet (1.8 to 2.4 meters).

Bernadette was playing with her sister and a friend when she claimed she saw a beautiful lady dressed in white who was standing above a rose bush. The lady was smiling at her. Bernadette tried to speak to her but could not. Bernadette then returned home.

The lady told Bernadette that the water was for the sick and asked her to tell people about the spring.
The local bishop investigated the apparition and declared the lady was the Virgin Mary. The bishop gave Bernadette communion and asked her to pray for the sick. Several years later, Bernadette was canonized as a saint. Her body is on display at the Sanctuary of Our Lady of Lourdes.

Drugs can also be used as part of a religious or spiritual ceremony.

Drugs affect the way our bodies and brains work.
Drugs that affect the way we feel include:
cannabis and synthetic cannabinoids
amphetamines and methamphetamine
opiates (including heroin)

some antidepressants (e.g. amitriptyline, fluoxetine)
some antipsychotics (e.g. chlorpromazine, haloperidol)

some antidepressants

Some drugs can affect the way our bodies and minds work for a long time after we stop taking them. This is known as a withdrawal effect.
The effects of drugs on our bodies and minds can vary from person to person. The effects of drugs can also change over time, as our bodies and minds become used to them.
Some drugs can cause other health problems, including:
cancers (e.g. bladder, breast, liver, mouth, skin)
heart disease and stroke
dementia and brain damage
mental health problems, including psychosis (e.g. hallucinations and delusions)
Other health problems caused by drugs include:
urinary tract infections (UTIs)

chronic hepatitis C
